## Specification Management

> Delete this section if OpenSpec is not configured. See `## Development Tools > OpenSpec` for setup.

Specs and change proposals are managed through OpenSpec. This is the single source of truth for what the system should do and how it should be built.

| Location | Contents |
|----------|----------|
| `openspec/specs/` | Active specifications -- one per feature area. Each has YAML frontmatter (`id`, `title`, `status`, `created`, `updated`). |
| `openspec/changes/` | Change proposals -- one directory per change (`<slug>/`), containing `proposal.md`, `design.md`, `tasks.md`, and spec deltas. |

**Role conventions:**
- **Analyst** writes new specs to `openspec/specs/` and creates change proposals (`proposal.md`) when updating existing specs.
- **Architect** fills in `design.md` and `tasks.md` within a change proposal, and produces spec deltas.
- **Developer** reads tasks from `openspec/changes/<slug>/tasks.md`, applies spec deltas after implementation.
- **Reviewer** checks spec currency: are deltas applied, does the implementation match the spec?

When no change proposal exists (ad-hoc work), specs in `openspec/specs/` are still the reference for requirements and architecture.

